                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d120">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/181<hi rend="superscript"
                    >2/10</hi>: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hinkle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ciudad Trujillo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-31T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >May 31, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 2:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>85. Legation’s telegram No. 83, May 30, 3 p.m. Doctor Troncoso later in the day
                    called me to say he had talked over the matter with General Trujillo who stated
                    that he wished to reiterate his desire to cooperate in this and any other way
                    and that whenever the officers arrive he himself would undertake conversations
                    with them at his house accompanied possibly by an aide. The President said that
                    General Trujillo welcomed having the conversations under the auspices of the
                    Chief of Mission and that the matter would be kept in strict confidence between
                    himself, General Trujillo and myself.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hinkle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
